quest_title: The number of reflexive relations of a set with four elements is equal to
explanation_txt:
Consider a set \(A = \{a_1, a_2, a_3, ... , a_n \} \)

\( A \times A = \{ (a_1,a_1), (a_a, a_2), ... , (a_2,a_2), ... (a_3, a_3), ..., (a_n, a_n) \} \)

The reflexive relations are subsets of \( \{ (a_1,a_1), (a_2,a_2), ... (a_n,a_n) \} \).

So, the superset of reflexive relations has \(n\) elements.

Total number of reflexive relations in a set with n elements \(=2^{n} \).

Therefore, total number of reflexive relation set with 4 elements \(=2^{4} \).

quest_title: For a moving body at any instant of time
ans1_txt: If the body is not moving, the acceleration is necessarily zero
ans2_txt: If the body is slowing, the retardation is negative
ans3_txt: If the body is slowing, the distance is negative
ans4_txt: If displacement, velocity and acceleration at that instant are known, we can find the displacement at any given time in future
explanation_txt:
If we know the displacement \(x_{0}\), velocity \(v_{0}\) and acceleration \(a\) of the moving body, we can calculate the displacement of the body at a later time by using formula \(s=ut+\cfrac{1}{2}at^{2}\).

All other options are incorrect.

Suppose you threw a ball vertically upward with an initial velocity. At the maximum height, the body is momentarity rest i.e. not moving but it still has acceleration directed downwards due to gravity.

If the body is slowing, its retardation is positive.

When the body is slowing, its acceleration is opposite to the direction of velocity but still can traverse distance in the direction of velocity making the distance travelled +ve.
